‚ÄúThey are counting on us to work together to solve these problems and make Virginia work better for everyone, no matter who they are or where they live.

‚ÄúThey are counting on us to deal with each other with civility and understanding, ready to acknowledge that we all came here with the goal of helping the people we serve.‚Äù

‚ÄúThey are counting on us to use every dollar they send us wisely, to the greatest possible benefit to our economy and their lives.

‚ÄúVirginians are counting on us to answer big challenges with big solutions, even if that requires us to put the common good ahead of our own partisan instincts.‚Äù

‚ÄúOur counterparts in Washington D.C. remind us daily of how easy it is to allow good-faith ideological disagreements to devolve into partisan warfare that drowns out the needs of the people.

‚ÄúThese proposals are solutions to problems that stand between us and the future our fellow Virginians deserve.‚Äù

‚ÄúDuring the campaign I was encouraged to see leaders in the other party agree to close a loophole in our ethics laws that allows public officials to spend campaign money for personal use.

‚ÄúMy team and I will continue that policy over the next four years so that men and women who make mistakes and serve their time can reenter society as full partners in our democracy, not second-class citizens.‚Äù

‚ÄúOn the first day of this session, Governor McAuliffe spoke to you about the importance of second chances in our criminal justice system.

‚ÄúWe can invest the significant revenues Clean Energy Virginia will generate to create clean energy jobs in rural communities, help families lower their electrical bills, and solidify our position as a global leader in renewable energy.‚Äù
‚ÄúI will also support a bill this session that will allow us to take full advantage of this process by joining a coalition of states called the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative, or RGGI.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe Clean Energy Virginia initiative is an incredible opportunity to create the next generation of energy jobs and lead the fight against climate change -- and my administration will implement it fully.‚Äù

‚ÄúLast year, Governor McAuliffe signed an Executive Directive to begin the process of capping carbon emissions from Virginia‚Äôs electric utilities and use the power of the market to foster growth and innovation in the clean energy sector.‚Äù

‚ÄúAs a native of the Eastern Shore, a scientist, and a resident of Hampton Roads, I can tell you personally that, no matter what politicians in Washington say, climate change is real.

‚ÄúLet‚Äôs reverse that troubling trend by passing no-excuse absentee voting, so more people can have a say in their future without jumping through unnecessary hoops.‚Äù
‚ÄúUnfortunately, Virginia law imposes many onerous and unnecessary restrictions on voting that discourage participation for many people.‚Äù

‚ÄúVoting is the most fundamental action a citizen can take in a democracy.

‚ÄúAs we begin our work, let‚Äôs ensure that all Virginians can realize their potential, no matter who they are, where they live, or whom they love.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis Commonwealth is home to people from every corner of the globe, every faith tradition, every political perspective and every income level.

‚ÄúBuilding a better Virginia for everyone means embracing and leveraging the incredible diversity of the people who live here.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe must act together this year to keep guns out of the hands of people who should not have them.‚Äù
‚ÄúAs long as the people who sent us all here continue to cry out for solutions to the epidemic of gun violence, we will fight on this ground.‚Äù
‚ÄúAs long as schools, churches, offices and concert venues are exposed to horrific, preventable violence, we will fight on this ground.‚Äù
‚ÄúAs long as Virginians‚Äô lives are at risk because there are too many guns in the hands of people who would use them to harm others, we will fight on this ground.‚Äù

‚ÄúQuality and affordable women‚Äôs health care is a constitutional right and an economic imperative ‚Äì it is also a personal decision.‚Äù
‚ÄúAs we work to expand health coverage, we should also make it easier for Virginia women to access reproductive health care, and oppose any effort to make it harder.‚Äù

‚ÄúExpanding Medicaid is the best way for us to make life better for Virginians and truly open a new era of policymaking in the Commonwealth of Virginia.
 
Let‚Äôs get it done this year.‚Äù

‚ÄúBipartisanship has been the watchword of the first few days of this session, and for that I am thankful.
 
We all recognize the extraordinary changes that voters made to this Assembly in November.
 
They expect us to deliver on the mandate they sent.‚Äù

‚ÄúThese men and women are not living the lives they deserve.
 
They are not making their fullest contribution to their communities or our economy.

‚ÄúEvery single Virginian you meet is someone‚Äôs son or daughter, and many tell tales of the daily agony they experience dealing with preventable health challenges.‚Äù

‚ÄúEvery year, I visit the Remote Area Medical Clinic in Wise County to help thousands of people get check-ups and treatment that they usually cannot access because they don‚Äôt have health insurance.‚Äù

‚ÄúMedicaid expansion is an opportunity to bring our tax dollars home and transform the lives of nearly 400,000 people who lack coverage today...

...As a physician, I believe that expanding Medicaid is a matter of basic economic justice.‚Äù
‚ÄúI am committed to working with the men and women of the General Assembly to expand Medicaid this year.‚Äù

‚ÄúWe are in the midst of a revolution with respect to how we research, prevent and treat a range of conditions that have historically cost too many people their productivity or even their lives.
 
I want VA to lead that revolution and to reap the economic benefits it will bring.‚Äù

‚ÄúEducation is a key predictor of a person‚Äôs prospects for lifetime success.
 
And so is health care.‚Äù
‚ÄúFinally, as we build an education system that prepares every child to succeed, we should make sure schools have the resources to educate students with special needs or learning disabilities.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe introduced budget includes more than $500 million in new funding for school divisions across VA...which will help these schools empower at-risk students to keep pace with their peers across VA, so that every child can enter the workforce ready to succeed on day one.‚Äù

‚ÄúAs we work to attract the best educators and staff on the planet, we should also recognize that a child‚Äôs prospects for lifetime success are far too often determined by the school they attend.‚Äù

‚ÄúQuality teachers are critical to educational success. So are school support staff...

These men and women play an essential role in the education of our young people and we should make sure every school can hire the best.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe should also work together now and in the years to come to make Virginia a leader in teacher pay -- so that the best and brightest come to our schools and stay for their entire careers.‚Äù

‚ÄúVirginia is home to some of the best schools on Earth ‚Äì and we should strive every day to make them better.
 
But we are also home to schools that struggle.
 
One of the most urgent reasons that some schools are falling behind is a nationwide shortage of qualified educators.‚Äù
‚ÄúBuilding a better Virginia for every family starts with offering every single child a world-class education, no matter who they are or where they live.‚Äù
‚ÄúIf we work together, we can build on our advantages in workforce development and make sure every Virginian can get the training she needs to build a successful career right at home.‚Äù

‚ÄúI hope you will accept the proposal in the introduced budget to increase funding for the New Virginia Economy Workforce Credential Grant Program...

Since its inception, this program has helped Virginians attain 4,595 industry credentials. More than 90% have gotten a job.‚Äù
‚ÄúThe centerpiece of that agenda is a plan to pay tuition and fees for any Virginian who pursues a credential in a high-demand field, if they commit to at least one year of public service.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe are also beginning the work to implement a proposal I made during the campaign called G3, which is short for Get Skilled, Get a Job, and Give Back.‚Äù
‚ÄúIf we are going to make Virginia work better for everyone, strengthening our workforce development system and expanding access to registered apprenticeships are key.‚Äù
‚ÄúI am committed to working with you to create more opportunities for Virginia workers to get a good job that empowers them to provide for their families and lead productive lives.‚Äù

‚ÄúTonight, I will lay out an agenda designed to reinforce the things that are working, and to fix the things that aren‚Äôt.
 
If we take these steps, we will answer the charge our voters gave us to make VA work better for everyone, no matter who they are or where they are from.‚Äù

‚ÄúFor many people, this is the best place on earth to live and work.
 
But while so many Virginians share in the opportunity and prosperity of a thriving state, those benefits have eluded too many of our neighbors for too long.‚Äù

‚ÄúThose of you who know me, know the Eastern Shore shaped who I am.

It‚Äôs a quiet place. A place of humility.

It‚Äôs a place where they teach the old lessons, the ones about loving our neighbor as ourselves.

And it‚Äôs a place that reminds us of Virginia‚Äôs contradictions.‚Äù
‚ÄúIn an era of social media and cable news, in a building filled with advocates, partisans and pundits, staying on the right path can be difficult.‚Äù

‚ÄúThat is a simple statement.
 
But far too often, public servants with the best of intentions find themselves pushed and pulled by forces that do not align with that goal.‚Äù
‚ÄúI believe Virginians select their leaders for one reason: to make this Commonwealth work better for them and their families, no matter who they are or where they live.‚Äù

‚ÄúFinally, I would like to share my best wishes for Speaker Bill Howell and his family. He served this Commonwealth with distinction for nearly 30 years and I know we are all praying for his speedy recovery.‚Äù

‚ÄúI would like to thank Terry and Dorothy McAuliffe for their tremendous service to this great Commonwealth.
 
It was an honor to serve with them over the past four years and Virginia is better off for their leadership.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe could not be here tonight were it not for the bravery and sacrifice of men and women who wear uniforms of every sort to keep our communities, our Commonwealth and our country safe.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis management team can be an example to our friends in the corporate world.

When people say, ‚Äòwe can‚Äôt find enough women, or enough diverse candidates for leadership roles,‚Äô I say‚Äîyou‚Äôre not looking hard enough.‚Äù
‚ÄúThis cabinet is led by women. And like this new General Assembly, it is also one of the most diverse in our history.‚Äù

‚ÄúOne of the most important duties of the men and women of my cabinet is to oversee the work of 110,000 of the most talented and dedicated public servants anywhere in the world.
 
Please join me in thanking our state employees for the outstanding work they do for all of us.‚Äù

‚ÄúNext, I am pleased to be joined by a diverse group of talented and dedicated men and women who will serve as my cabinet and closest advisors in the years to come.
 
Thank you for your commitment to serving this Commonwealth.‚Äù

‚ÄúI want to recognize Lieutenant Governor Justin Fairfax and Attorney General Mark Herring.
 
It was an honor to campaign with you both and I look forward to the great things we will get done together over the next four years.‚Äù

‚ÄúFirst, please join me in welcoming the love of my life and the First Lady of the Commonwealth of Virginia, Pam Northam and our daughter Aubrey...

Pam, I cannot wait to see what you accomplish for the people of Virginia as First Lady.‚Äù

because we have a lot of work to do.‚Äù

‚ÄúThose words have stuck with me all these years because they‚Äôre so clear.

‚ÄúMy dad‚Äôs advice stayed with me when I reached the Virginia Military Institute and was given a different kind of compass, in the simple words of the VMI honor code:

‚ÄòA Cadet will not lie, cheat, steal, nor tolerate those who do.‚Äô‚Äù

‚ÄúIf things get dark or foggy, if you can‚Äôt find your way‚Äîkeep your eye on the compass.

‚ÄúWhen I was just old enough to take to the water myself, my dad helped me build a rowboat and launch it, with strict instructions: stay close to home.‚Äù
